						<div class="postbody">Alright, so let me summarize the whole phenomenon to make sure I understood it correctly:<br /><br />My TV renders borders that are outside the usual &quot;NES display area&quot; and fills them with the global background color of the game.<br /><br />In the current example, the global background color is very bright while the regular dominant color of the background tiles is black.<br /><br />Now, according to Joe, the green stripes are kind of a reflection from the bright area on the left side that are visible because the dominant color is black.<br />According to Drag, it isn't reflection, but actually something that's drawn by the cathode ray due to some internal ways a CRT TV renders an image.<br /><br />Is this correct so far?<br /><br />So, this means two things:<br />1. The green light does not come from some magnetic interferences in my room or something like that.<br />2. The green light is not the result of my TV having been broken at one point in all the years.<br />The effect would still be visible with a brand new TV of the same brand in a room without any interferences.<br /><br />Did I understand all this corectly?<br /><br />Furthermore, is there any website on the internet where this phenomenon is described? If this is a side effect of NTSC CRT TV technology, shouldn't half of the &quot;Ninja Gaiden&quot; players experienced this? I'd really like to read more about it.</div>

